('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:tf:d13a8ec5', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A file-size calculation for an image should be left in bits as the final answer, even if the question asks for KB."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "The formula gives bits first, but that is only the first step — you must convert (÷8 for bytes, ÷1,000 per unit after that) into whatever unit the question actually asks for."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:tf:7921b742', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Metadata is not needed to correctly reconstruct an image from its stored binary data."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Metadata (such as width, height and colour depth) is essential — without it, software could not correctly split the raw pixel data back into the right grid."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:learn:06300d17', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How is a bitmap image stored as binary?", "reading": "<h4>Pixels: the grid that makes up a bitmap image</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>bitmap image</strong> is made up of a grid of tiny coloured dots called <strong>pixels</strong> (\"picture elements\"). Zoom in far enough on any digital photo or icon and you can see the individual pixels that make it up.</li>\n<li>Every pixel stores a <strong>binary code</strong> that represents its own colour. The whole image is stored as one long sequence of these binary codes, one pixel after another.</li>\n<li>To display the image again, the software reads the binary codes back out in the same order and colours in each pixel accordingly — rebuilding the original grid.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>A simple example: a 1-bit (monochrome) pixel grid</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>With a <strong>colour depth of just 1 bit</strong>, each pixel can only be one of <strong>two</strong> colours — shown below as a filled square (storing 1) or an outlined square (storing 0). This 5×5 grid stores a simple plus-sign shape this way:</li>\n</ul>\n<svg viewBox=\"0 0 172 172\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"A 5 by 5 grid of pixels forming a plus-sign shape, where filled squares are pixels storing binary value 1 and outlined squares are pixels storing binary value 0\">\n<rect x=\"2\" y=\"2\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"36\" y=\"2\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"70\" y=\"2\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"currentColor\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"104\" y=\"2\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"138\" y=\"2\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"2\" y=\"36\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"36\" y=\"36\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"70\" y=\"36\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"currentColor\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"104\" y=\"36\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"138\" y=\"36\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"2\" y=\"70\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"currentColor\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"36\" y=\"70\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"currentColor\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"70\" y=\"70\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"currentColor\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"104\" y=\"70\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"currentColor\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"138\" y=\"70\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"currentColor\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"2\" y=\"104\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"36\" y=\"104\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"70\" y=\"104\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"currentColor\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"104\" y=\"104\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"138\" y=\"104\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"2\" y=\"138\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"36\" y=\"138\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"70\" y=\"138\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"currentColor\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"104\" y=\"138\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"138\" y=\"138\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n</svg>\n<p>Reading the middle row left to right gives the binary pattern <strong>1 1 1 1 1</strong> — five pixels, five bits. A real photograph works exactly the same way, just with a much bigger grid and many more bits stored per pixel.</p>\n<h4>Why the grid order matters</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Every pixel''s binary code must be stored in the <strong>same fixed order</strong> (usually left-to-right, top-to-bottom) so the software knows exactly which code belongs to which position in the grid. Get the order wrong and the picture is scrambled, even if every individual colour code is correct.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What is a pixel?", "options": ["The smallest single point of colour that makes up a bitmap image", "The total number of pixels used to measure an image''s resolution", "A unit used to measure how much free storage space is left on a device", "The file extension used to identify which image format has been used"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A bitmap image is built from a grid of pixels — each pixel is the smallest single point of colour in that grid, storing a binary code for its own colour."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:learn:f1bafb24', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "What is colour depth, and how many colours can it represent?", "reading": "<h4>Colour depth: bits per pixel</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Colour depth</strong> is the number of <strong>bits</strong> used to store the colour of a <strong>single pixel</strong>. A bigger colour depth means more bits are spent describing each pixel''s colour.</li>\n<li>Because each extra bit doubles the number of different binary codes available, the number of possible colours a colour depth of <strong>n</strong> bits can represent is <strong>2<sup>n</sup></strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Colour depth</th><th>Calculation</th><th>Possible colours</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1 bit</td><td>2<sup>1</sup></td><td>2 (e.g. black and white)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2 bits</td><td>2<sup>2</sup></td><td>4</td></tr>\n<tr><td>4 bits</td><td>2<sup>4</sup></td><td>16</td></tr>\n<tr><td>8 bits</td><td>2<sup>8</sup></td><td>256</td></tr>\n<tr><td>24 bits</td><td>2<sup>24</sup></td><td>16,777,216 (\"true colour\")</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h4>Worked example: finding the minimum colour depth needed</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Step</th><th>What you do</th><th>Result</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>A designer needs each pixel to display at least 16 different colours. Try increasing colour depths and calculate 2 to the power of n until it reaches 16.</td><td>2<sup>4</sup> = 16</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>State the minimum colour depth needed.</td><td>4 bits</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h4>Why this matters for the exam</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>You may be asked to go either direction: calculate <strong>how many colours</strong> a given colour depth allows (2<sup>n</sup>), or work out the <strong>minimum colour depth</strong> needed for a target number of colours (find the smallest n where 2<sup>n</sup> is big enough).</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A retro game uses a colour depth of 5 bits per pixel. How many different colours can each pixel display?", "options": ["16", "32", "64", "10"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "2 to the power of the colour depth gives the number of possible colours: 2 to the power of 5 = 32."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:learn:6e96c13f', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "What is resolution, and how does it affect an image?", "reading": "<h4>Resolution: the total pixel count</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Resolution</strong> is the total number of pixels that make up an image, found by multiplying its <strong>width</strong> (in pixels) by its <strong>height</strong> (in pixels).</li>\n<li>A higher resolution means the image is made up of <strong>more</strong>, smaller pixels — so it can show finer detail. A lower resolution means fewer, larger pixels, which can make the image look blocky when it is enlarged.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Worked example</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Step</th><th>What you do</th><th>Result</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>An image is 150 pixels wide and 100 pixels tall. Multiply width × height.</td><td>150 × 100 = 15,000 pixels</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>State the resolution.</td><td>15,000 pixels</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h4>Resolution is not the same as colour depth</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>These two terms are easy to mix up, but they describe completely different things: <strong>resolution</strong> is HOW MANY pixels there are; <strong>colour depth</strong> is how many BITS are used for each individual pixel''s colour. An image can have a high resolution with a low colour depth (lots of pixels, few colours), or the other way round.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "An image measures 150 pixels wide and 100 pixels tall. What is its resolution (total number of pixels)?", "options": ["15,000 pixels", "1,500 pixels", "25,000 pixels", "150,000 pixels"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Resolution = width × height = 150 × 100 = 15,000 pixels."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:learn:dd07f9ba', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Quality vs file size: the trade-off from colour depth and resolution", "reading": "<h4>Both factors push quality and file size the same way</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Increasing <strong>colour depth</strong> allows more possible colours per pixel, giving smoother, more realistic colour — but it means more bits are stored for every single pixel, so the file gets <strong>bigger</strong>.</li>\n<li>Increasing <strong>resolution</strong> shows more fine detail, because there are more pixels in the grid — but there is also more pixel data to store overall, so the file gets <strong>bigger</strong> too.</li>\n<li>There is no way to improve quality using either factor without also increasing the file size — it is always a trade-off.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Worked example: doubling resolution</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Step</th><th>What you do</th><th>Result</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>An image is 100 × 100 pixels with an 8-bit colour depth. Find the file size in bits, then bytes, then KB.</td><td>8 × 100 × 100 = 80,000 bits → 10,000 bytes → 10 KB</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>Double BOTH the height and width to 200 × 200 pixels, keeping the colour depth the same. Recalculate.</td><td>8 × 200 × 200 = 320,000 bits → 40,000 bytes → 40 KB</td></tr>\n<tr><td>3</td><td>Compare the two file sizes.</td><td>40 KB is 4× the original 10 KB</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h4>Why doubling resolution QUADRUPLES the file size</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Doubling both height and width doesn''t just double the pixel count — it multiplies it by <strong>2 × 2 = 4</strong>, because BOTH dimensions have doubled. This is a common trap: many students expect doubling resolution to double the file size, when it actually roughly quadruples it (when both height and width are doubled).</li>\n</ul>", "question": "An image''s file size is 10 KB. If you double BOTH its height and width in pixels, keeping the colour depth the same, what is its new approximate file size?", "options": ["20 KB", "40 KB", "10 KB", "80 KB"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Doubling both dimensions multiplies the pixel count by 2 × 2 = 4, so the file size roughly quadruples: 10 KB × 4 = 40 KB."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:learn:6e949072', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Metadata: why is extra information stored with an image file?", "reading": "<h4>What is metadata?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Metadata</strong> is extra information stored alongside an image''s pixel data, describing the image itself rather than being part of the picture. Typical metadata for an image file includes its <strong>width</strong>, <strong>height</strong>, <strong>colour depth</strong> and <strong>file type</strong> (the image format used).</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Why metadata is essential, not optional</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Without knowing the <strong>width</strong>, the software reading the file would have no way to tell where one row of pixels ends and the next one begins — the pixel data is really just one long string of bits with no natural breaks.</li>\n<li>Without knowing the <strong>colour depth</strong>, the software would not know how many bits to read for each individual pixel''s colour code, so it could not correctly split the pixel data into separate pixels at all.</li>\n<li>Without the <strong>file type</strong>, the software would not know which set of rules to use to interpret the stored bits in the first place.</li>\n<li>In short: the raw pixel data on its own is meaningless without the metadata needed to correctly reconstruct it back into a grid.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Metadata adds to the file size</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Because metadata is extra information on top of the pixel data, a real image file is always <strong>slightly bigger</strong> than the size given by colour depth × height × width alone. Exam calculations usually ignore this small extra amount unless a question specifically tells you to include it.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Which piece of information is stored as part of an image file''s metadata?", "options": ["The width and height of the image, in pixels", "The exact colour value of every single pixel in the image", "The name of the software currently being used to view the file", "The total amount of free storage space left on the device"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Metadata describes the image itself — such as its width, height, colour depth and file type — so the software can correctly rebuild the pixel grid. The pixel colour values are the picture data itself, not metadata."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:learn:df640328', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Worked example: calculating an image file''s size", "reading": "<h4>The formula</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>File size (bits) = colour depth (bits per pixel) × height (pixels) × width (pixels)</strong></li>\n<li>Always calculate the answer in <strong>bits</strong> first, then convert into whatever unit the question actually asks for.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Worked example</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Step</th><th>What you do</th><th>Result</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>An image is 60 pixels tall and 50 pixels wide, with a colour depth of 8 bits. Multiply colour depth × height × width.</td><td>8 × 60 × 50 = 24,000 bits</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>Convert bits into bytes by dividing by 8.</td><td>24,000 ÷ 8 = 3,000 bytes</td></tr>\n<tr><td>3</td><td>Convert bytes into a sensible unit by dividing by 1,000.</td><td>3,000 ÷ 1,000 = 3 KB</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h4>Show every step, every time</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>OCR-style marking usually splits calculation marks between the <strong>working</strong> and the <strong>final answer</strong> — so writing down all three steps (multiply, then ÷8, then ÷1,000) protects your marks even if you slip on the arithmetic somewhere along the way.</li>\n<li>Remember the real file will be a little bigger than this because of <strong>metadata</strong> — but unless a question tells you to include it, calculate using colour depth × height × width alone.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "An image is 40 pixels tall and 25 pixels wide, with a colour depth of 8 bits. What is its file size in bytes?", "options": ["1,000 bytes", "8,000 bytes", "125 bytes", "10,000 bytes"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "8 × 40 × 25 = 8,000 bits. 8,000 ÷ 8 = 1,000 bytes."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:misc:6b92e350', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Believing that more pixels always means a better image, without thinking about the resulting file size.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> More pixels (a higher resolution) does usually improve detail — but it also increases the <strong>file size</strong>, because there is more pixel data to store. Quality and file size always move together, so \"more pixels is always simply better\" ignores the real storage cost.</p>", "question": "Is it true that increasing resolution improves an image with no downside at all?", "options": ["No — it also increases the file size, since more pixel data has to be stored", "Yes — resolution has no effect at all on an image''s file size, it only ever affects quality", "No — increasing resolution actually makes an image lower quality", "Yes — but only for images using a colour depth below 8 bits"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A higher resolution means more pixels, which means more pixel data to store — so the file size also increases. There is always a trade-off."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:misc:ed0b2962', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking a colour depth of n bits gives n possible colours — e.g. assuming 4 bits means 4 colours.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> It is <strong>2 to the power of n</strong>, not n. A colour depth of 4 bits gives 2<sup>4</sup> = <strong>16</strong> possible colours, not 4. Each extra bit DOUBLES the number of colours available, rather than adding a fixed amount.</p>", "question": "A colour depth of 4 bits is used. How many different colours can each pixel represent?", "options": ["4", "8", "16", "20"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "2 to the power of 4 = 16, not 4. Colour depth and number of colours are related by 2 to the power of n, not a simple multiplication."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:misc:42ddadf7', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Confusing colour depth with resolution — describing colour depth as ''the number of pixels in the image''.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> <strong>Colour depth</strong> is the number of bits used for ONE pixel''s colour. <strong>Resolution</strong> is the total number of pixels in the whole image (height × width). They are independent — an image can have a high resolution with a low colour depth, or the other way round.</p>", "question": "Which statement correctly distinguishes colour depth from resolution?", "options": ["Colour depth is bits per pixel; resolution is the total number of pixels in the image", "Colour depth and resolution both measure exactly the same thing", "Resolution is bits per pixel; colour depth is the total number of pixels in the image instead", "Colour depth measures screen size; resolution measures file type"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Colour depth = bits used per pixel''s colour. Resolution = total pixel count (height × width). They are two separate, independent properties of an image."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:misc:8a80c10c', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Leaving a file-size calculation answer in bits, because the multiplication already produced ''a number'' that looks like an answer.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Colour depth × height × width always gives the answer in <strong>bits</strong> first — that is only the first step. You must then divide by 8 to reach bytes, and keep dividing by 1,000 for each unit up the ladder until you reach the unit the question actually asked for.</p>", "question": "A calculation gives 24,000 bits, and the question asks for the answer in KB. What should you do next?", "options": ["Divide by 8 to get bytes, then divide by 1,000 to get KB", "Write down 24,000 as the final answer, already correct in KB", "Multiply the bits total by 8 to reach bytes", "Divide the bits total by 1,000 only, then stop working"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "24,000 bits ÷ 8 = 3,000 bytes, then ÷ 1,000 = 3 KB. Both conversion steps are needed to reach the unit asked for."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:misc:46c602db', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Assuming doubling an image''s resolution (both height and width) only doubles the file size.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Doubling BOTH height and width multiplies the total pixel count by <strong>2 × 2 = 4</strong>, not 2 — so the file size roughly QUADRUPLES, not doubles. Only doubling a single dimension (just the width, say) would double the pixel count.</p>", "question": "An 8-bit image is 50 × 50 pixels. Both its height and width are doubled to 100 × 100 pixels. What happens to the file size?", "options": ["It roughly doubles", "It roughly quadruples", "It stays exactly the same", "It is cut roughly in half"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Doubling both dimensions multiplies the pixel count by 2 × 2 = 4, so the file size roughly quadruples, not doubles."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:misc:2f8116e6', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking metadata is optional extra information that could be deleted without affecting how the image displays.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Metadata (especially the <strong>width</strong>, <strong>height</strong> and <strong>colour depth</strong>) is required to correctly decode the pixel data. Without it, the software has no way to know where one row of pixels ends or how many bits belong to each pixel — the raw data becomes meaningless.</p>", "question": "What would happen if an image file''s metadata (width, height, colour depth) were removed, leaving only the raw pixel data?", "options": ["The software could no longer correctly rebuild the pixel grid from the data", "Nothing at all — the image would carry on displaying exactly as it did before, with no problems", "The file size would increase to compensate", "The image would automatically display in black and white"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Without metadata like width and colour depth, software cannot tell where rows of pixels begin and end, or how many bits belong to each pixel — so it cannot correctly reconstruct the image."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images:tips:028a0737', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-6-data-storage-images', '1.2.6 Data Storage: Images', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — Show-your-working ladder: the image file-size calculation", "reading": "<p>A typical question: <em>\"A photo is 40 pixels wide and 30 pixels tall, with a colour depth of 8 bits per pixel. Calculate the file size in bytes. Show your working.\"</em> [2 marks] Here is the same answer at every level:</p>\n\n<p><strong>❌ 0 marks:</strong> \"1,200 bytes\"</p>\n<ul>\n<li>No working shown. Even a correct final answer with nothing behind it risks losing the working mark entirely if it happens to be wrong.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>⚠️ 1 mark:</strong> \"8 × 40 × 30 = 9,600\"</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Valid working is shown (1 mark), but the answer was never converted into bytes and stated as a final answer — the second mark is for the CONVERTED answer in the unit asked for.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>✅ 2 marks:</strong> \"8 × 40 × 30 = 9,600 bits <strong>(1)</strong>. 9,600 ÷ 8 = 1,200 bytes <strong>(1)</strong>.\"</p>\n\n<p><strong>Why this matters even if your arithmetic slips:</strong> OCR-style marking separates the WORKING mark from the ANSWER mark. If your method is correct but you slip on the final division, you can still keep the working mark — but only if you actually wrote the working down.</p>", "question": "You calculate 8 × 40 × 30 = 9,600 correctly, but then wrongly divide by 100 instead of 8 and write ''96 bytes''. What mark do you get out of 2?", "options": ["0, because the final stated answer is wrong", "1 — the working mark for the correct multiplication step", "2, since your working clearly shows you understood the method", "It depends entirely on which calculator you used"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The multiplication step (8 × 40 × 30 = 9,600 bits) is valid working, so it earns the working mark even though the final conversion — and therefore the answer mark — was wrong."}'::jsonb)
